From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude.ai.2026@simonlaux.de>
Date: Mon, 20 Jul 2026 21:10:44 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 58/58] web-app: custom voice-message mini-player + Media
 Session (experimental)

Phase A3 of the experimental audio player. All behind the existing
experimentalAudioPlayerControls setting; with it off, the global bar and
playback behave exactly as before (native re-parenting, no media session).

- GlobalVoiceMessagePlayer: with the setting on, replace re-parenting the
  native <audio> singleton into the bar with the A1/A2 CustomAudioControls
  driving THE SINGLETON directly (audioRef wraps ctx.audioElement in a stable
  useMemo so its effects don't re-subscribe each render, src = currentSrc).
  A2's restore guard is a live-playback no-op here (audioRef.current IS
  ctx.audioElement), so it never rewinds the message that's playing. Left of
  the controls: a compact sender line (avatar + display name + chat name),
  clickable to jump to that message via the existing jumpToMessage mechanism
  (same-account) or CommandPalette's __selectAccount idiom (cross-account).
  Sender/chat are fetched once per message with useRpcFetch(getMessage /
  getBasicChatInfo). The close button is unchanged.
- CustomAudioControls is exported from the AudioPlayer module and gains a
  `compact` prop that drops its 300px min-width so it fits the ~295px
  chat-list column.
- NextVoiceMessagePlayerContext exposes the validated currMessage and a
  playNext(): the ended-driven auto-advance and playNext now share one
  advanceOrStop() code path (advance to nextMessage if ready, defer while it
  loads, else stop); no behavior change when the setting is off.
- navigator.mediaSession (guarded, only while a src is playing and the setting
  is on): metadata is PRIVACY-SUPPRESSED by default -- generic localized
  "Voice message" title, no artist/artwork -- because these controls can leak
  onto the lock screen (forum 5423). A new desktop setting
  voiceMessageMediaSessionDetails (default false) opts in to sender name /
  chat name / sender avatar. Action handlers: play/pause -> singleton,
  seekbackward/seekforward (+/-10s clamped), seekto -> singleton currentTime,
  nexttrack -> ctx.playNext (= auto-advance). positionState is set on the
  singleton's timeupdate/ratechange/durationchange, throttled ~1Hz and
  guarded/try-caught (setPositionState throws on non-finite duration).
  Handlers + metadata are nulled when playback stops / the setting turns off /
  on unmount.
- pure helpers mediaSessionMetadata(suppressed, label, {sender,chat,avatar})
  and clampSeek(t, delta, duration) live in GlobalVoiceMessagePlayer/
  mediaSession.ts (no browser/React imports) with mocha cases for the
  suppressed-vs-detailed choice, avatar guard, and seek clamping.

Also folds in A2/recorder refinements that were sitting uncommitted in the
worktree (they interleave with the files above and A3 relies on several):
singleton clear-on-ended in MediaPlayerMutexContext, the restorePosition
helper + one-way restore guard in CustomAudioControls, the shared-promise
peaks cache + document-relative waveform-worker URL, positionStore test
extraction, and the recorder's callback-driven live waveform.

Adversarial-review hardening (same feature, no behavior change with the
setting off): propagate singleton seeks back to the bubble's muted element
via a delta-guarded 'seeked' mirror (fixes the display desync and the dueling
positionStore writers in one place); let the restore guard skip only once the
same-src singleton has real progress (>=1s) so auto-advance onto a half-heard
message still restores; render the mini-player's sender row only for a
resolved queued message (draft previews and in-flight fetches no longer show
an empty focusable jump button, and nexttrack is unregistered when there's no
next); read the fetch `result` (not the lingering one) so the display and OS
metadata never attribute the playing message to the previous sender; push a
fresh mediaSession positionState immediately after a seek; reorder the
sequential-playback staleness guard ahead of the stop branch so a stale parked
ended event can't stop an unrelated message; fall back to the generic label
when a detailed metadata title would be blank; and bump the chat-name contrast
to meet WCAG AA.
